			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Help for a new bard<a name="46502"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 16 04 7:23 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
~~First off, are there any other armor quests that can be done for upgrades (lets call them newb) past the songweavers armor?
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Well, yes and no.
<br />
The next step up from Songweaver's armor is Lambent, which you can do in your late 20s and early 30s. Lambent armor is decent if you really like doing quests, unfortunately completing the quests requires that you turn in gemstones, and for the the money you'd spend on the gemstones you can buy comparable or better armor in bazaar.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
~~And second, I am still hunting in EC, which is giving me somewhat good xp, but is there a better place that I can go that will help me learn to play the class? (I have done crushbone, Pc, all the xp camps with my cleric so I am not interested in visiting those places again).
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Anywhere you can get a group, really. This might mean going to the &quot;xp camps&quot; since that's where the groups are. I personally do a lot of LDoN adventures.
<br />
Your life and duties as a bard are going to change throughout the levels as you get new songs. For instance, you don't get mezz until 15, and being able to mezz an add while twisting songs in one of the more important skills to learn. Later on, you'll get charm, resist songs, damage shields, over-haste, and spell-haste. 
<br />
Just try each of your songs as you get them and get a sense of what they do, how long they last, whether or not the buffs stack, etc. Do some research in the guides and song lists if you're unsure of what a particular song does.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
I really want a place that will let me solo while gaining good xp (I am not looking for a quick level, rather a good learning experience).
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
This is going to turn into a flame war if we're not careful. There's another thread on this board that's pretty much dominated by an argument over whether or not soloing IS a good learning experience. There's a lot of bards who believe that if you solo too much you'll miss a lot of learning experiences that come from grouping.
<br />
Make sure you group a lot, is all I'm going to say here.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
~~Last, I have looked at the links that are here, read everything that was there, but I am still confused about some things. Mainly, the art of twisting songs and the usuage of instruments. Both have left me extrememly confused. I would imagine that the art of twisting comes more with practice than anything else, but I am missing the basics somewhere in all the posts that I have read.
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Twisting is simple. Let's use Chant of Battle and Hymn of Restoration since I know you have both of those.
<br />
Start Chant of Battle. The casting window will go away after a second and the Chant of Battle icon will appear in your song buffs. Once the icon appears, start Hymn of Restoration. After a second, the heart icon for Hymn will appear next to the muscled arm for Chant of Battle.
<br />
Now you have the bonus for BOTH Chant of Battle and Hymn of Restoration. This is a simple two-song twist. Every bard should be able to do a three song twist without any of the icons fading.
<br />
Does that make sense?
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
 And instruments, well, I am completly in the dark. If we have a weapon, and if we do not need to purchase and instrument to gain skill (wind, percussion,etc), then why do we need to buy instruments at all?
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Well, our instruments make most of our songs more powerful.
<br />
If Hymn of Restoration regenerates 5 HP per tick, equipping a Stringed Instrument with a 2.0 modifer will make it regenerate 10 HP per tick.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
