			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Help for a new bard<a name="46531"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 16 04 11:05 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
 ~~Is there a place that is recomended to &quot;practice&quot; soloing for those times you don't want to be in a group~~that's the best way I can put it, I guess.
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
You know what? I do agree with you.
<br />
If I were playing a newbie toon and grouping with a newbie bard, I'd rather they have learned their songs and capabilities on their own, then futz up the group messing around with songs that they don't know anything about.
<br />
A good place to practice skills on your own is the Sarnak fort in Lake of Ill Omen. It's rarely camped, and you can practice breaking the camp apart and pulling singles out to the lawn.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Has anyone gotten the armor that is bought through points in LDoN? And if so, is it worth the points that you have to spend?</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Well, all the LDoN armor is decent, but most of it is way too expensive for what it gives you. The devs are considering the possibility of either increasing LDoN point awards or decreasing the cost of some armors, but it's not really certain how that's going to turn out. I guess if you were doing a lot of Tak dungeons the 20-point Tak armor is a decent upgrade from Songweaver. Unfortunately even if you do hard LDoN straight from 20 you might get one piece of Tak armor at 25.
<br />

<br />
I kept my newbie armor until my late 30s when I could start doing other things for income like kite Hill Giants for coin, or when Rathe Mountains were way too camped I'd go to Tenebrous Mountains and quest a Rallic Pack for sale in bazaar (easy 1k). Then I just spent several nights accumulating platinum, and went to bazaar and bought some decent mid-level gear.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">How do you know which instrument to buy, when to use it and when not to use it, and whats the best that you can recommend for my level at decent price.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Shass already listed the Combine instruments, which are good. If you are really cheap, you can camp Cht'Thk Ash Beetles for Ivory Horn (wind instrument) and Cht'Thk Swarmers for Flawless Ivory Horn (brass instrument) both of which drop in Shadeweaver's Thicket off of the Shar Vahl PoK book. You won't need either until level 20 or so anyway.
<br />

<br />
During your early levels, you're not going to be using instruments that much. You'll wield your drum when travelling (Selo's Accelerando makes you even faster with a drum equipped), a wind instrument when invis is needed to travel through a difficult area, and a stringed instrument during group downtime while singing Hymn of Restoration. You only need a brass instrument at your level for AE kiting, which is a form of soloing that provides xp very very fast - but since you've already said you don't want to solo for xp, I doubt you'll be doing that.<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" /> While in a group, you'll probably be melee-ing a lot until your higher levels, when your melee damage starts to suck and you can benefit your group a lot more by equipping an instrument while playing a song.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">"And now for my next miracle, I will turn water... into funk!"
</span></td>
